Day 19 – Seeker Tool

Seeker = OSINT-based geolocation tool
Used for gathering target device location information through phishing techniques.

Category:
Social engineering / OSINT tool

Purpose:
- Collect geolocation data
- Gather device information
- Educational security awareness testing

How It Works (High-Level):
- Creates a fake webpage
- Sends link to target
- If target opens link and grants permission,
  the tool collects location data from browser

Information It Can Collect:
- Latitude & Longitude
- Device type
- Browser information
- IP address
- Operating system

Important Concept:
Seeker depends on human interaction.
User must open the link and allow location access.

Why It Is Dangerous:
- Invades privacy
- Can track physical location
- Used in stalking or malicious attacks

Why It Is Studied in Cybersecurity:
- Understanding social engineering risks
- Learning about privacy vulnerabilities
- Awareness training

Defensive Measures:
- Do not click unknown links
- Disable automatic location sharing
- Review browser permissions
- Use VPN for privacy
- Be cautious on social media

Legal Warning:
Using Seeker without consent is illegal.
Only use in lab or authorized testing environment.

Key Learning:
Human trust and browser permissions are major security weaknesses.
Security is not just technical — it is behavioral.
